from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder
categorical_columns = data.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns
# Initialize a Label Encoder
label_encoder = LabelEncoder()

# Create a copy of the data to avoid modifying the original DataFrame
data_label_encoded = data.copy()

# Apply label encoding to each categorical column
for column in categorical_columns:
    data_label_encoded[column] = label_encoder.fit_transform(data[column])

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Selecting the features based on their positive correlation with 'Satisfied'
feature_columns = positive_correlation_with_satisfied.index.drop('Satisfied')  # Exclude the target itself
features = data_label_encoded[feature_columns]
target = data_label_encoded['Satisfied']

# Splitting the data into training and test sets (70/30)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(features, target, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Show the sizes of the splits
X_train.shape, X_test.shape, y_train.shape, y_test.shape

Decision Tree¶

In [20]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

# Initialize the Decision Tree Classifier
dt_classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)

# Set up the hyperparameters grid for tuning
param_grid_dt = {
    'max_depth': [None, 10, 20, 30],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 10, 20],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 5, 10]
}

# Setting up the GridSearchCV for Decision Tree
grid_dt = GridSearchCV(dt_classifier, param_grid_dt, cv=3, scoring='accuracy', verbose=1)
grid_dt.fit(X_train_scaled_df, y_train)

# Evaluate the best model from grid search on the test set
dt_best = grid_dt.best_estimator_
y_pred_dt = dt_best.predict(X_test_scaled_df)

Random Forest¶

In [23]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# Initialize the Random Forest Classifier
rf_classifier = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)

# Set up the hyperparameters grid for tuning
param_grid_rf = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200],  # Number of trees
    'max_depth': [None, 20],  # Maximum depth of trees
    'min_samples_split': [20],  # Minimum number of samples required to split
    'min_samples_leaf': [10]  # Minimum number of samples required at each leaf node
}

# Setting up the GridSearchCV for Random Forest
grid_rf = GridSearchCV(rf_classifier, param_grid_rf, cv=3, scoring='accuracy', verbose=1)  # Reduced cv to speed up
grid_rf.fit(X_train_scaled_df, y_train)

# Evaluate the best model from grid search on the test set
rf_best = grid_rf.best_estimator_
y_pred_rf = rf_best.predict(X_test_scaled_df)

from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix

# Assuming you have y_pred_dt and y_pred_rf from your earlier model predictions

# Compute confusion matrices
cm_dt = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_dt)
cm_rf = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred_rf)

# Plotting the confusion matrices
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(9, 4))

ax[0].set_xticklabels(['Negative', 'Positive'])
ax[0].set_yticklabels(['Negative', 'Positive'])

Plot the results¶

In [27]:
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

import numpy as np

# Generate the reports (repeating for context)
dt_report = classification_report(y_test, y_pred_dt, output_dict=True)
rf_report = classification_report(y_test, y_pred_rf, output_dict=True)

# Extract metrics for Decision Tree
dt_metrics = {
    'Accuracy': dt_report['accuracy'] * 100,  # Convert to percentage
    'Precision': dt_report['macro avg']['precision'] * 100,  # Convert to percentage
    'Recall': dt_report['macro avg']['recall'] * 100,  # Convert to percentage
    'F1-Score': dt_report['macro avg']['f1-score'] * 100  # Convert to percentage
}

# Extract metrics for Random Forest
rf_metrics = {
    'Accuracy': rf_report['accuracy'] * 100,  # Convert to percentage
    'Precision': rf_report['macro avg']['precision'] * 100,  # Convert to percentage
    'Recall': rf_report['macro avg']['recall'] * 100,  # Convert to percentage
    'F1-Score': rf_report['macro avg']['f1-score'] * 100  # Convert to percentage
}

# Metrics names and values for plotting
metric_names = list(dt_metrics.keys())
dt_metric_values = [dt_metrics[metric] for metric in metric_names]
rf_metric_values = [rf_metrics[metric] for metric in metric_names]

# Prepare data for plotting
n_groups = len(metric_names)
index = np.arange(n_groups)
bar_width = 0.35

# Create a larger bar plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 6))  # Larger figure size
bar1 = ax.bar(index, dt_metric_values, bar_width, label='Decision Tree', color='blue')
bar2 = ax.bar(index + bar_width, rf_metric_values, bar_width, label='Random Forest', color='green')

# Add text annotations on the bars
for bars in (bar1, bar2):
    for bar in bars:
        yval = bar.get_height()
        ax.text(bar.get_x() + bar.get_width()/2, yval + 0.5, f'{yval:.2f}%', ha='center', va='bottom', color='black', weight='bold')

ax.set_xlabel('Metrics')
ax.set_ylabel('Percentage')
ax.set_title('Comparison of Decision Tree and Random Forest Model Performance')
ax.set_xticks(index + bar_width / 2)
ax.set_xticklabels(metric_names)
ax.set_ylim(90, 100)  # Adjust as needed based on actual scores
ax.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
